WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.280
Okay, cool.

00:00:06.280 --> 00:00:12.560
So I want to talk to you all about how you can take your R packages to new frontiers

00:00:12.560 --> 00:00:15.520
with R OpenSci's R-Universe.

00:00:15.520 --> 00:00:17.200
So a little bit about me.

00:00:17.200 --> 00:00:23.480
So two years ago, I had a lightning talk at RStudio Global about my first package, which

00:00:23.480 --> 00:00:25.520
was a huge milestone for me.

00:00:25.520 --> 00:00:28.520
So I come from psychology.

00:00:28.520 --> 00:00:37.080
We do some coding to do our stats and our stuff, but there's no formal training.

00:00:37.080 --> 00:00:42.680
So getting an R package out there, that was a huge deal for me.

00:00:42.680 --> 00:00:47.840
And my package is about plotting brains in ggplot.

00:00:47.840 --> 00:00:52.279
This is so much fun to work on, and it uses simple features for those who know about that.

00:00:52.279 --> 00:00:57.880
So it's basically a map, but instead of the globe, it's your brain.

00:00:57.880 --> 00:00:59.919
And it makes me very happy.

00:00:59.919 --> 00:01:01.439
So there's two parts of this package.

00:01:01.439 --> 00:01:06.000
It's ggplot2 package with simple features, and there's a second part with plotly and

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:08.760
like a three-dimensional swively brain.

00:01:08.760 --> 00:01:09.760
Very, very fun.

00:01:09.760 --> 00:01:14.680
IT loves it when we want to put that online.

00:01:14.680 --> 00:01:22.519
So these packages for this package at that point lived only on GitHub, because I did

00:01:22.519 --> 00:01:28.839
not have the headspace or understanding of how to get it on CRAN, and we want our packages

00:01:28.839 --> 00:01:29.839
on CRAN.

00:01:29.839 --> 00:01:37.720
Like I wanted to be an R developer, so to be that, I needed to have a package on CRAN.

00:01:37.720 --> 00:01:39.680
Like I couldn't just have it on GitHub.

00:01:39.680 --> 00:01:41.639
And why do we want our packages on CRAN?

00:01:41.639 --> 00:01:46.480
Now, that's because that's where, like, everyone else is getting their packages from.

00:01:46.480 --> 00:01:48.919
That's where users expect the packages from.

00:01:49.120 --> 00:01:54.199
They don't have, like, a mental model necessarily about where the packages are coming from.

00:01:54.199 --> 00:01:55.760
They're coming from CRAN.

00:01:55.760 --> 00:01:57.199
You do install packages.

00:01:57.199 --> 00:01:59.360
They're coming from CRAN.

00:01:59.360 --> 00:02:05.320
So I want them there, but, like, getting there...

00:02:05.320 --> 00:02:06.320
That is work.

00:02:06.320 --> 00:02:09.759
That is a lot of work.

00:02:09.759 --> 00:02:10.919
So I had this package.

00:02:10.919 --> 00:02:17.559
It had this stuff, and it, like, was working on my code, getting it ready for CRAN, and

00:02:17.559 --> 00:02:19.600
I hit this roadblock.

00:02:19.600 --> 00:02:21.399
My package is too big.

00:02:21.399 --> 00:02:24.520
There's a 5 megabyte limit.

00:02:24.520 --> 00:02:28.320
There's a lot of data behind these plots.

00:02:28.320 --> 00:02:29.320
And I was struggling.

00:02:29.320 --> 00:02:34.759
So the first thing I did, I saw I split it up in two, and I no longer have one package

00:02:34.759 --> 00:02:35.759
to get on CRAN.

00:02:35.759 --> 00:02:38.119
I have two packages to get on CRAN.

00:02:38.119 --> 00:02:39.119
Right.

00:02:39.119 --> 00:02:40.119
Okay.

00:02:40.119 --> 00:02:46.080
But I did the work, and I got them both on there, and I'm super proud.

00:02:46.080 --> 00:02:56.800
Now, a magic thing happened when this package went from living on GitHub to living on CRAN.

00:02:56.800 --> 00:03:02.759
And that is all the user installation problems just poofed away.

00:03:02.759 --> 00:03:09.320
Like, before, I would have, like, issues constantly with people, like, it's not installing, it's

00:03:09.320 --> 00:03:10.520
not installing.

00:03:10.520 --> 00:03:14.720
And I'm, like, I don't know why.

00:03:14.720 --> 00:03:16.800
Because I'm not a developer.

00:03:16.800 --> 00:03:19.880
I don't necessarily understand what's behind this.

00:03:19.880 --> 00:03:21.839
But CRAN just fixed all of that.

00:03:21.839 --> 00:03:24.759
But the thing is...

00:03:24.759 --> 00:03:26.520
You know how you have different maps?

00:03:26.520 --> 00:03:27.520
Okay.

00:03:27.520 --> 00:03:30.960
So the globe, like, the map itself is the same.

00:03:30.960 --> 00:03:35.600
But you can kind of split the world up in different ways, depending on what you want

00:03:35.600 --> 00:03:36.600
to look at.

00:03:36.600 --> 00:03:42.839
By continents, by country, political borders, like, geographical landmarks, whatever.

00:03:42.839 --> 00:03:44.679
We do the same with the brain.

00:03:44.679 --> 00:03:48.199
Don't think, like, neuroscientists, we're not, like, the brain is one thing, no, it's

00:03:48.199 --> 00:03:50.240
so many features.

00:03:50.240 --> 00:03:54.199
And everyone works on, like, their own versions of all of these features.

00:03:54.199 --> 00:03:56.720
There's so many of them.

00:03:56.720 --> 00:03:58.440
I have, like...

00:03:58.440 --> 00:04:03.679
I think we have about 30 requests right now for new what we call atlases.

00:04:03.679 --> 00:04:06.240
And we have 20 already.

00:04:06.240 --> 00:04:09.720
And all of this all of these are over 5 megabytes.

00:04:09.720 --> 00:04:11.720
They will never go on CRAN.

00:04:11.720 --> 00:04:15.720
I cannot get them there unless I completely figure out how to get away from the size of

00:04:15.720 --> 00:04:18.399
them.

00:04:18.399 --> 00:04:22.720
And all of these have issues with installation.

00:04:22.720 --> 00:04:26.720
And it's frustrating for me and it's frustrating for my users, because I have no idea how to

00:04:26.720 --> 00:04:27.720
help them.

00:04:27.720 --> 00:04:33.720
I don't have an overview of what is making this installation not working.

00:04:33.720 --> 00:04:39.320
So what the hell does CRAN do that makes this work?

00:04:39.320 --> 00:04:41.640
I just dived into it.

00:04:41.640 --> 00:04:46.920
I need to figure out why CRAN installations work.

00:04:46.920 --> 00:04:49.600
And I got to learn about binaries.

00:04:49.600 --> 00:04:58.839
Now binaries are a thing I know nothing about.

00:04:58.839 --> 00:05:02.880
But I'm still gonna try to explain it to you.

00:05:02.880 --> 00:05:09.799
So imagine you're, like, these two R users and you want to connect to this you want to

00:05:09.799 --> 00:05:13.760
get to this star, which is the package you want to go to.

00:05:13.760 --> 00:05:19.160
So when you're what we're calling compiling from source, you know, once in a while you

00:05:19.160 --> 00:05:22.359
write install packages, blah, blah.

00:05:22.359 --> 00:05:24.559
And it goes, oh, there is no binary available.

00:05:24.559 --> 00:05:25.959
Do you want to compile from source?

00:05:25.959 --> 00:05:30.839
And you go, yeah, sure, I need this package compiled from source.

00:05:30.839 --> 00:05:32.600
And it does, like, all of this stuff.

00:05:32.600 --> 00:05:34.160
And you don't know what it is.

00:05:34.160 --> 00:05:35.959
And hopefully that's gonna work.

00:05:35.959 --> 00:05:37.880
And you're gonna be happy and you get your package.

00:05:37.880 --> 00:05:40.600
So you're, like, following this map.

00:05:40.600 --> 00:05:41.600
You're here.

00:05:41.600 --> 00:05:42.600
You're gonna go there.

00:05:42.600 --> 00:05:43.600
You're following all the steps.

00:05:43.600 --> 00:05:44.600
You're getting there.

00:05:44.600 --> 00:05:45.600
Great.

00:05:45.600 --> 00:05:46.600
And then another user comes along.

00:05:46.600 --> 00:05:48.000
Their OS is something else.

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:51.040
So they're starting their journey from another place.

00:05:51.040 --> 00:05:53.440
So they need to do something else.

00:05:53.440 --> 00:05:56.399
There's another road map for them to get there.

00:05:56.399 --> 00:05:58.440
And what if you're in uncharted territory?

00:05:58.440 --> 00:06:05.000
Like, you're on an OS that we don't we don't know how to get you to this place.

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:08.359
Compile from source failed.

00:06:08.359 --> 00:06:11.260
That is what my users are struggling with.

00:06:11.260 --> 00:06:12.260
So why?

00:06:12.260 --> 00:06:13.399
So what are binaries?

00:06:13.399 --> 00:06:16.160
So binaries circumvent this entire thing.

00:06:16.160 --> 00:06:18.359
I love sci-fi.

00:06:18.359 --> 00:06:21.399
So for me, they're like a wormhole.

00:06:21.399 --> 00:06:24.279
So it's a prebuilt thing.

00:06:24.279 --> 00:06:26.679
Like, you know where you are.

00:06:26.679 --> 00:06:28.359
You know where you're going.

00:06:28.359 --> 00:06:32.279
And you just, like, there's a rift in space time and you just get there.

00:06:32.279 --> 00:06:33.279
That's what the binary does.

00:06:33.559 --> 00:06:35.839
Like, it just gets you there.

00:06:35.839 --> 00:06:37.519
Awesome.

00:06:37.519 --> 00:06:42.000
So when you have your package on GitHub, you have no binaries.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:46.559
It's all compiling from source, which makes all of the madness.

00:06:46.559 --> 00:06:47.559
It's awesome for me.

00:06:47.559 --> 00:06:48.559
Easy.

00:06:48.559 --> 00:06:49.559
I just get my code up there.

00:06:49.559 --> 00:06:55.899
Just get it to pass, like, the most important checks of our command so that it installs.

00:06:55.899 --> 00:06:59.079
But it can be hard for the user because the binaries are not there.

00:06:59.079 --> 00:07:03.040
CRAN is awesome because it's easy for the users.

00:07:03.040 --> 00:07:04.040
Binaries are there.

00:07:04.040 --> 00:07:05.040
There's vetting.

00:07:05.040 --> 00:07:06.040
There's checking.

00:07:06.040 --> 00:07:07.040
Like Joe was just talking about.

00:07:07.040 --> 00:07:10.480
Like, there's this whole infrastructure around it that makes it work for the users.

00:07:10.480 --> 00:07:14.399
But it is so much work for me.

00:07:14.399 --> 00:07:15.559
And I'm not a full time developer.

00:07:15.559 --> 00:07:16.559
I'm a scientist.

00:07:16.559 --> 00:07:21.119
So I need something, like, in the middle.

00:07:21.119 --> 00:07:29.720
And like two months after I had that lightning talk, ROpenSci comes with their RUniverse.

00:07:29.720 --> 00:07:35.700
The RUniverse is a piece of software magic that you cannot believe.

00:07:35.700 --> 00:07:41.519
So Jeroen Ooms, who is the one who is behind this at ROpenSci, he's a magician, this stuff

00:07:41.519 --> 00:07:42.519
is so good.

00:07:42.519 --> 00:07:47.839
So it makes, like, its own little CRAN-like server.

00:07:47.839 --> 00:07:49.559
But without the vetting and stuff.

00:07:49.600 --> 00:07:51.880
But it works just like CRAN.

00:07:51.880 --> 00:07:53.160
There's no curation.

00:07:53.160 --> 00:07:54.160
You design your own.

00:07:54.160 --> 00:07:56.019
You put the packages you want in there.

00:07:56.019 --> 00:07:57.220
You get your own universe.

00:07:57.220 --> 00:08:01.880
And it's kind of organized through, like, user or organizations through, like, GitHub,

00:08:01.880 --> 00:08:04.619
GitLab, Bitbucket, stuff like that.

00:08:04.619 --> 00:08:06.920
It's quite easy to connect to.

00:08:06.920 --> 00:08:07.920
So let's have a look.

00:08:07.920 --> 00:08:14.640
So this is my GTSEG RUniverse with some of the packages that are in this universe.

00:08:14.640 --> 00:08:17.040
And there's a couple of things we want to look at.

00:08:17.040 --> 00:08:19.279
Number one, this is the main package.

00:08:19.279 --> 00:08:21.119
You see the little green ribbon?

00:08:21.119 --> 00:08:23.279
That's because it's on CRAN.

00:08:23.279 --> 00:08:28.359
So you get this nice little thing.

00:08:28.359 --> 00:08:33.520
If your package is on CRAN, our universe will detect it and it gives you this lovely ribbon

00:08:33.520 --> 00:08:36.179
and you can go, yay.

00:08:36.179 --> 00:08:40.520
But the really exciting part is this part over here.

00:08:40.520 --> 00:08:48.400
Which is telling me that for R version 4.3 and R version 4.2, I have binaries for both

00:08:48.400 --> 00:08:49.400
Windows and Mac.

00:08:49.400 --> 00:08:51.679
And this is the most magic thing I know.

00:08:51.679 --> 00:08:55.280
Because the binaries are there, you don't have to think about them anymore.

00:08:55.280 --> 00:08:59.799
I don't need to understand what they are other than the wormhole.

00:08:59.799 --> 00:09:02.000
And it is just working.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:09.119
And once this came into place, I don't have installation issues anymore.

00:09:09.119 --> 00:09:10.679
Like, it's just working.

00:09:10.679 --> 00:09:13.719
It is magic.

00:09:13.719 --> 00:09:18.000
And you know when you have your package on GitHub, you have to install either the dev

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:20.080
tools or the remote package.

00:09:20.080 --> 00:09:24.840
And then you have to use the special install function to get the blah, blah.

00:09:24.840 --> 00:09:26.080
Notice this piece of code.

00:09:26.080 --> 00:09:28.960
This is all you need to install from this universe.

00:09:28.960 --> 00:09:34.559
You just have to plug in that I want you to look in this universe for packages that I'm

00:09:34.559 --> 00:09:35.559
looking for.

00:09:35.559 --> 00:09:41.000
And in this case, I'm asking to install the main ggsec package.

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:43.719
It will look for it first in the ggsec universe.

00:09:43.719 --> 00:09:45.960
It will find it.

00:09:45.960 --> 00:09:49.479
And then for all the dependencies, it's gonna jump to the next because I don't have those

00:09:49.479 --> 00:09:50.479
in my universe.

00:09:50.479 --> 00:09:51.479
There's way too many.

00:09:51.479 --> 00:09:56.840
It's just gonna jump to the next, which is a CRAN mirror.

00:09:56.840 --> 00:09:57.840
Super simple.

00:09:57.840 --> 00:10:00.039
I just have that in my readme now.

00:10:00.039 --> 00:10:02.760
Don't have to think about it.

00:10:02.760 --> 00:10:07.840
So why would you want to have your package on the R universe?

00:10:07.840 --> 00:10:10.900
You might, like me, have all of these packages that are huge.

00:10:10.900 --> 00:10:16.820
And even if they weren't huge, I'm not completely convinced that the CRAN team would be super

00:10:16.820 --> 00:10:21.099
happy if I start flooding it with, like, brain atlas packages.

00:10:21.099 --> 00:10:23.260
It's extremely niche.

00:10:23.260 --> 00:10:24.340
And there's a lot of them.

00:10:24.340 --> 00:10:25.419
And they keep, like...

00:10:25.419 --> 00:10:28.179
It's just, like, exploding.

00:10:28.179 --> 00:10:32.080
You might have learner tutorials and you're giving it to your students and you need them

00:10:32.080 --> 00:10:34.619
to run stuff and they're not installing.

00:10:34.619 --> 00:10:39.119
Again, binaries, they're gonna install easily.

00:10:39.119 --> 00:10:42.919
You might have dev versions that you also want to distribute with binaries.

00:10:42.919 --> 00:10:45.640
Because again, it's gonna install easily.

00:10:45.640 --> 00:10:51.359
Or you might want to collect packages for your company or your lab.

00:10:51.359 --> 00:10:57.000
So you have, like, a common ground of, like, where your packages live.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:00.320
And it doesn't have to be packages you have made.

00:11:00.320 --> 00:11:06.599
You can put other packages into the R universe from other people if you want to lock them

00:11:06.599 --> 00:11:09.840
down or, like, I had a...

00:11:09.840 --> 00:11:16.719
So one of these packages that I'm gonna talk to you about soon depended on another neuroscience

00:11:16.719 --> 00:11:20.320
R package that had a bug at some point.

00:11:20.320 --> 00:11:26.719
And I could go back to my R universe and say, I want you to depend on the previous version

00:11:26.719 --> 00:11:28.080
of this package.

00:11:28.080 --> 00:11:31.599
Because that makes my universe work again until they fix the bug.

00:11:31.599 --> 00:11:37.320
So I could fix it without, like, actually fixing it.

00:11:37.320 --> 00:11:43.000
Now a thing I noticed when I was setting up this universe was that in the beginning, it

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:46.280
was in a kind of disorganized state.

00:11:46.280 --> 00:11:51.719
Because these packages, this whole ecosystem comes from a large European research project

00:11:51.719 --> 00:11:53.599
I was on called LifeBrain.

00:11:53.599 --> 00:11:59.039
And we had several packages come out of LifeBrain that were not brain related.

00:11:59.039 --> 00:12:00.760
They were stats related or something else.

00:12:00.919 --> 00:12:05.039
And my packages were, like...

00:12:05.039 --> 00:12:09.080
It was making all these other packages less visible, and it was kind of cluttering it

00:12:09.080 --> 00:12:10.080
up.

00:12:10.080 --> 00:12:11.080
And it also...

00:12:11.080 --> 00:12:15.960
The neuroscience people weren't necessarily interested in these other packages.

00:12:15.960 --> 00:12:20.099
Some of them who are more, like, social science related.

00:12:20.099 --> 00:12:24.599
So I realized, like, I should probably switch things up a bit.

00:12:24.599 --> 00:12:30.400
So because GitHub is quite easy when you're an academic, because you get free stuff, I

00:12:30.400 --> 00:12:34.159
just made a new organization specifically for these packages.

00:12:34.159 --> 00:12:37.880
And I only did that because of our universe.

00:12:37.880 --> 00:12:46.799
So that I could get, like, one unified universe where all of the packages for this suite live.

00:12:46.799 --> 00:12:51.840
And because they're now all collected in the same spot, it means that it's also easier

00:12:51.840 --> 00:12:57.580
for me to start getting contributions, because I just include them into this organization.

00:12:57.580 --> 00:13:02.179
It's not tied to my, like, Horizon Europe project.

00:13:02.179 --> 00:13:07.619
It's tied to just this contribution from the community.

00:13:07.619 --> 00:13:14.179
And because, like, all the installation issues poofed by this thing, I could use that headspace

00:13:14.179 --> 00:13:19.260
to start making a package that would enable people to make their own atlases, so that

00:13:19.260 --> 00:13:26.820
I didn't have to make it for everyone, because I just don't have time for that.

00:13:26.820 --> 00:13:33.419
So I made this other package that contains tooling to create your own GDSEG atlas.

00:13:33.419 --> 00:13:37.419
It's a monster of a thing, because it calls a lot of, like, other neuroscience stuff,

00:13:37.419 --> 00:13:39.659
and it's, like, Jesus.

00:13:39.659 --> 00:13:47.419
But it's there, and it works for me, and it has worked for a couple of other people.

00:13:47.419 --> 00:13:52.500
And I'm excited to see that it is being used.

00:13:52.500 --> 00:13:59.340
So the R universe has a lot of extra stuff going on as well.

00:13:59.340 --> 00:14:06.020
So in this, like, extra package that I have, it's first iteration also contained a dataset,

00:14:06.020 --> 00:14:13.820
a table in this case, about where all of the atlases that were compatible with this suite

00:14:13.820 --> 00:14:14.820
lived.

00:14:14.820 --> 00:14:19.619
With the idea that they would probably not be in the same spot, because R universe didn't

00:14:19.619 --> 00:14:20.979
exist when I started on this.

00:14:20.979 --> 00:14:24.659
I had started on this before that.

00:14:24.659 --> 00:14:30.340
And we would need to, like, manually update this every time, like, a new atlas came in.

00:14:30.340 --> 00:14:33.979
And that is, like, a bit of work.

00:14:33.979 --> 00:14:38.940
I'm, like, I prefer things to be a bit more automatic than that.

00:14:38.940 --> 00:14:43.979
A good friend of mine once said I became a developer because I'm lazy.

00:14:43.979 --> 00:14:45.700
I think that's kind of true for me, too.

00:14:45.700 --> 00:14:49.500
So anything that can just happen automatically, I'm very, very fond of.

00:14:49.500 --> 00:14:52.340
And through the R universe, I can do that.

00:14:52.340 --> 00:14:58.299
So now instead of a table, I just have a bit of code and a function that just looks that

00:14:58.299 --> 00:15:05.979
calls the ROpenSci API and asks, hey, can you list all the packages in this universe?

00:15:05.979 --> 00:15:06.979
And it does.

00:15:06.979 --> 00:15:09.659
And I just make it into a table.

00:15:09.659 --> 00:15:11.659
That's it.

00:15:11.659 --> 00:15:14.659
That is it.

00:15:14.659 --> 00:15:16.179
I'm so happy.

00:15:16.179 --> 00:15:19.460
You have no idea.

00:15:19.460 --> 00:15:22.580
It's such a powerful piece.

00:15:22.580 --> 00:15:26.419
And, like, I'm not going to cover everything that it does.

00:15:26.419 --> 00:15:27.419
It does so many things.

00:15:27.419 --> 00:15:28.580
It's the API.

00:15:28.580 --> 00:15:30.219
It will render your documentation.

00:15:30.219 --> 00:15:35.539
It will give you, like, pages to browse through.

00:15:35.539 --> 00:15:40.200
And I know there's a lot of things going on in the pipeline.

00:15:40.200 --> 00:15:49.099
So while we do love CRAN for its consistency, for the fact that it's something we can connect

00:15:49.099 --> 00:15:57.380
to, it is safe, it is there, it does a lot of magic for us, we can all expand our horizons

00:15:57.380 --> 00:15:59.739
by a lot.

00:15:59.739 --> 00:16:02.059
By using the R universe.

00:16:02.059 --> 00:16:04.340
Because it is such a powerful piece of tool.

00:16:04.340 --> 00:16:10.419
And I thoroughly, thoroughly believe if you have a package on GitHub, you should have

00:16:10.419 --> 00:16:13.419
a package in ROpenSci's R universe.

00:16:13.419 --> 00:16:14.419
Thanks.

00:16:14.739 --> 00:16:15.739
So...

00:16:15.739 --> 00:16:22.739
Thanks so much, Mo.

00:16:22.739 --> 00:16:29.419
Tyler, could you come up and get plugged in here?

00:16:29.419 --> 00:16:32.099
You have time for one question here.

00:16:32.099 --> 00:16:37.140
Are there any advantages installing the package from R universe versus CRAN if it's available

00:16:37.140 --> 00:16:39.419
on both?

00:16:39.419 --> 00:16:45.619
So in my case, like, advantages and disadvantages, it kind of depends on the person that has

00:16:45.619 --> 00:16:48.059
set up the R universe.

00:16:48.059 --> 00:16:50.859
So in my case, if you're getting it...

00:16:50.859 --> 00:16:55.059
So ggsec, which is both on CRAN and on RU's universe, if you're getting it from the R

00:16:55.059 --> 00:16:57.460
universe, you're getting the development version.

00:16:57.460 --> 00:17:00.719
If you're getting it from CRAN, you're getting the release version.

00:17:00.719 --> 00:17:03.059
And I know several people who do it that way.

00:17:03.059 --> 00:17:06.020
It's not necessarily the way it's set up, but it might be.

00:17:06.020 --> 00:17:14.099
So the version on CRAN might be more stable to use, in a sense.

00:17:14.099 --> 00:17:16.900
So I think that's more of a preference.

00:17:16.900 --> 00:17:22.380
And probably, like, ask the developer which version is the preferred one.

00:17:22.380 --> 00:17:23.380
Yeah.

00:17:23.380 --> 00:17:24.380
Yeah.

00:17:24.380 --> 00:17:28.619
And then just real quick, have you received any pushback from your users who were like,

00:17:28.619 --> 00:17:30.060
no, I only want it from CRAN?

00:17:30.060 --> 00:17:32.260
Or are they just happy from wherever it comes from?

00:17:32.260 --> 00:17:33.260
Oh, no.

00:17:33.260 --> 00:17:34.260
I'm happy that it exists.

00:17:34.260 --> 00:17:40.900
No, like, so our neuroscience is like the hugest community in the world.

00:17:40.900 --> 00:17:44.979
So if something installs, they're just going to be happy.

00:17:44.979 --> 00:17:49.699
So if it's on R universe, like CRAN universe, GitHub, doesn't matter.

00:17:49.699 --> 00:17:53.339
If it installs and they can use it, they're happy.

00:17:53.339 --> 00:17:54.819
And that's an amazing place to be.

00:17:54.819 --> 00:17:55.819
Yeah.

00:17:55.819 --> 00:17:57.180
Let's give Mo one more round of applause.

00:18:03.260 --> 00:18:04.260
Thank you.

00:18:04.260 --> 00:18:05.260
Thank you.

00:18:05.260 --> 00:18:05.260


